          "body": "Ezekiel 43 is not a new chapter so much as an answer long withheld. From the moment the *kavod* rose from its threshold and moved eastward in Ezekiel 10:18-19, the entire book has been structured by its absence. Chapters 1-24 announced the coming judgment; chapters 8-11 showed the glory's departure in four agonizing stages; chapters 25-32 executed judgment on the nations; chapters 33-42 measured and described an empty house waiting for its occupant. Now in 43:1-5, the wait ends. The glory comes from the east, its voice like many waters, the earth luminous with its radiance. Ezekiel falls on his face — the same posture he took at the initial Chebar vision (1:28) and at the departure vision (3:23). The chapter's first five verses are the theological payoff of the entire prophetic corpus. No reader who has tracked the departure in chapters 10-11 can arrive at verse 5 — 'the glory of the Lord filled the house' — without feeling the weight of restoration. The house that was measured empty (chs. 40-42) is now full."
