          "body": "The chapter's second half (vv. 13-27) descends from theophany and declaration into precise measurements and ritual prescription. This descent is not anticlimactic — it is the chapter's argument made concrete. The altar cannot simply be built and used. Before the burnt offerings ascend (the approach-offerings of vv. 18, 24, 27), the altar itself must be consecrated by blood: sin-offering blood applied to all four horns, all four corners of the ledge, and the surrounding border (v. 20). The altar — the very instrument of atonement — is itself a defiled object requiring atonement (*kipher*, v. 20, 26). This theological point is the Old Testament anticipation of a New Testament principle: the means of cleansing must itself be clean. The seven-day cycle of sin offerings (vv. 22-26) echoes the priestly ordination of Leviticus 8-9 and the Tabernacle dedication, signaling that Ezekiel's restored worship stands in direct continuity with the Sinai covenant institutions. The eighth day (v. 27) then inaugurates the unending era of regular worship — burnt offerings and peace offerings ascending, and the divine declaration closing the chapter: 'I will accept you.' The *ratsah* (acceptance, favorable reception) of verse 27 is the resolution of everything the chapter has built toward: a holy God, a consecrated altar, a purified people, and divine pleasure in the approach."
