          "body": "Evangelical scholarship is rightly divided over the referent of Ezekiel's temple vision. Three main positions deserve honest presentation. The *literal-futurist* (premillennial) view, represented by Walvoord, Feinberg, and Block, holds that the vision describes an actual millennial temple to be built in Jerusalem during the thousand-year reign of Christ — the detailed measurements demand a literal fulfillment; the sacrificial system functions as memorial and educational in the millennial kingdom, not as repeated atonement (Hebrews 10:10 is not violated because the sacrifice is backward-looking, not forward-looking). The *symbolic-idealist* view, represented by Iain Duguid and others in the Reformed tradition, reads the entire vision as a symbolic portrayal of the New Covenant church — the perfect temple is Christ Himself and His body; the measurements convey completeness and holiness, not blueprint specifications. The *inaugurated-eschatological* view, developed by Vern Poythress and aligned with Revelation 21-22, holds that the vision is typologically fulfilled in the new heavens and new earth: John's vision of the new Jerusalem deliberately alludes to Ezekiel 40-48, and the physical river of life (Ezek. 47) and the open gates (Ezek. 48) find their antitype in Revelation's eternal city. What no orthodox interpreter disputes is the canonical truth that Ezekiel 43 announces: the God who departed in judgment will return in glory, will dwell with His people permanently, will require and provide cleansing, and will speak the final word — 'I will accept you.' That declaration has its ultimate Yes in 2 Corinthians 1:20 and its eternal habitation in Revelation 21:3."
